<div class="nytint-grid-container clearfix">
  
  <div class="nytint-discussion-content">
    <div class="rfd">
    <h1 class="nytint-post-headline">Even a Flawed Plan Will Be Useful</h1>
    
    <div class="nytint-mugshots">
        <img alt="Jeffrey Lewis" class="nytint-mug" src="http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2013/09/11/opinion/lewis/lewis-thumbStandard.jpg" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="nytint-post-leadin"><a href="http://www.miis.edu/about/newsroom/experts/jlewis">Jeffrey Lewis</a>  is director of the East Asia Nonproliferation Program at the Monterey Institute of International Studies.</p>
    
    <p class="pubdate"><strong>Updated</strong> September 11, 2013,  6:24 PM</p> 
    
    <div class="nytint-post">
      <p>A plan to secure Syria’s chemical weapons stockpiles doesn’t have to be perfect. But it will be better than any probable alternative.</p>

<p>A number of commentators have noted the slow progress of the United States in eliminating its own stockpile of chemical weapons under the Chemical Weapons Convention. But the reasons are completely irrelevant to the situation in Syria. It reflects local politics in the United States of siting and operating chemical weapons incinerators. Local environmental groups in Syria will not slow the work of the United Nations and Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons with <a href="http://seattletimes.com/html/politics/2009691650_apuschemicalweapons.html">lawsuits</a>.</p>

<div class="w190 right module"><div class="entry"><blockquote>It will be difficult, but not impossible. And if Assad reneged on his commitments, the United States would be in a better position to use force.</blockquote></div></div>

<p>In fact, the international community has moved faster when it mattered. The United Nations Special Commission in Iraq supervised “the destruction of over 480,000 liters of live chemical weapons agent, 28,000 chemical munitions and approximately 1.8 million liters, and over 1 million kilograms of some 45 different precursor chemicals” in a little less than two years -- from June 1992 to May 1994. </p>

<p>Although it is hard to know the size of Syria’s chemical weapons stockpile, estimates of 1,000 tons of various agents are pretty similar to <a href="http://www.fas.org/irp/gulf/cia/960715/72569.htm">pre-1991 estimates</a> in Iraq. This is not a dramatically different task, at least not in scale.></p>

<p>Prior to destruction, the United Nations consolidated Iraq’s stockpiles. Consolidating Syria’s chemical weapons stockpile would prevent their use by the military. The international community could consolidate Syria’s chemical weapons in a third country, where destruction could occur at a more leisurely pace. Jordan, for example, has made clear its <a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970203961204577269680793484776.html">preference</a> for a diplomatic solution to this crisis. Here is Amman’s chance to step up. </p>

<p>I don’t want to downplay the challenges of attempting to either destroy or remove chemical weapons stockpile in a situation as chaotic as war torn Syria. The inspectors who enter Syria will be taking real personal risks to make the world a safer place. But we’re not asking them to do something impossible or futile. </p>

<p>If we have the political will and reasonable expectations, a diplomatic solution offers a better way to reduce the threat from Syria’s chemical weapons than any of the other options currently on the table.</p>

<p>And if Assad were to renege on his commitments after surrender only a portion of the stockpile, the United States and its allies would be in a better legal and political position to use force, with fewer chemical weapons to target.</p>

<p><blockquote></p>

<p><em>Join <a href="http://www.facebook.com/RoomforDebate">Room for Debate on Facebook</a> and follow updates on <a href="http://twitter.com/roomfordebate">twitter.com/roomfordebate</a>. </em></p>

<p></blockquote></p>
    </div><!-- .nytint-post -->
    
    
    
